<div id="review_33788791" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/33788791" />
    <a title="Nate D" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/406701-nate-d"><img alt="Nate D" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1203897989p2/406701.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/33788791?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nate D" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nate D" href="/user/show/406701-nate-d">Nate D</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780393064537" href="/book/show/23959.The_Bedroom_Secrets_of_the_Master_Chefs">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">People who have already read the better Welsh like Trainspotting and Glue.</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/406701-nate-d?shelf=britain">britain</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/406701-nate-d?shelf=read-in-2008">read-in-2008</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer33788791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10809702596156769403">With <i>Ulysses</i> done, I need to read something fast, entertaining, pulpy. Thanks, Irvine Welsh.<br/><br/>This brow-leaping habit may be genetic. My mom apparently read <i>Salem&apos;s Lot</i> (King) right after <i>Anna Karenina</i> (Tolstoy).<br/><br/>...<br/><br/>Finished. Enjoyable, but a bunch of issues make this a clumsier Welsh effort overall:<br/>1. Guessed crux of climactic plot reveal in first 100 pages, and sort of knew how things would end.<br/>2. There were likeable characters, but not so much the main protagonists/antagonists (okay, hardly uniq</span>
  <span id="freeText10809702596156769403" style="display:none">With <i>Ulysses</i> done, I need to read something fast, entertaining, pulpy. Thanks, Irvine Welsh.<br /><br />This brow-leaping habit may be genetic. My mom apparently read <i>Salem's Lot</i> (King) right after <i>Anna Karenina</i> (Tolstoy).<br /><br />...<br /><br />Finished. Enjoyable, but a bunch of issues make this a clumsier Welsh effort overall:<br />1. Guessed crux of climactic plot reveal in first 100 pages, and sort of knew how things would end.<br />2. There were likeable characters, but not so much the main protagonists/antagonists (okay, hardly unique for Welsh, but <i>Glue</i> was so human that I hope for more now.<br />3. Inconsistent perspective never justified in any reasonable way.<br />4. Felt need to spell out the theme not once but twice, where tangential evidence had already sufficed.<br />5. Dialect toned down in a manner that makes me suspect Welsh was shooting for wider readability. But I've always enjoyed the dialect.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10809702596156769403" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


