  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2834153846" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2834153846" />
    <a title="April" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24591006-april"><img alt="April" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381369884p2/24591006.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2834153846?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="April" class="user" itemprop="url" name="April" href="/user/show/24591006-april">April</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2834153846&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2834153846" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4773119499982378485">This book was part of Derek T&apos;s collection that he was getting rid of during a move. He drove up a huge box of books for me from LA and this copy was in there--beaten up with a strip of black duct tape holding together the spine. How did it get that way? Was it read over and over or something, like a favorite book? Or did Derek find it? Or was it even his and did he even read it? I&apos;ll have to ask Derek.<br/><br/>A very intense read, as I suppose his other books are too. I&apos;ve only read <i>Trainspotting</i> and th</span>
  <span id="freeText4773119499982378485" style="display:none">This book was part of Derek T's collection that he was getting rid of during a move. He drove up a huge box of books for me from LA and this copy was in there--beaten up with a strip of black duct tape holding together the spine. How did it get that way? Was it read over and over or something, like a favorite book? Or did Derek find it? Or was it even his and did he even read it? I'll have to ask Derek.<br /><br />A very intense read, as I suppose his other books are too. I've only read <i>Trainspotting</i> and that was intense in a different way (all the drug usage and its consequences, the disgusting predicaments, and violence; although I suppose there was a bit of violence and disgusting predicaments in this book too). He leads us on to think along the same lines as Skinner as he searches for his father, for example with the vignette of Greg Tomlin looking at an old photo. <br /><br />Something kept throwing me off about Skinner--the fact that he was referred to as "Skinner" made me think of an older guy, like maybe in his mid-30s and a little washed out, instead of a younger, strapping, handsome fellow. (Probably due to an American TV reference.) So I kept thinking of this washed out character in his mid-30s doing all these crazy alcohol-fueled antics and having the thoughts and sex he had. I don't know, I just thought of him at that age through the whole book and kept needing the reminders that he was this strapping young guy just a couple years out of Uni. Anyway, that's mostly besides the point. <br /><br />The idea that someone could shift their physical deterioration to someone else was a new storyline concept to me and I found it interesting to see how it played out. The narrative perspective shifts were also an interesting call. I wasn't sure if it was necessary to do that, but I could see how it added interest and helped move the story along. <br /><br />I wonder if it had to end in one character's annihilation? Why couldn't they both continue to exist? And even maybe build a meaningful relationship together? I guess the ending had some vindication in some ways, but it also left me feeling empty and sad that something more meaningful couldn't be built from the previously misdirected or misplaced hatred that was meted out. I wanted reconciliation and a "Wow, so that's what was going on between us! I'm so glad we figured out this mystery. How crazy is all that??" I guess I was looking for a happier ending, but not all endings get to be happy.<br /><br />"But when Kay did enter the flat there was a distance about her and a resolve that he'd never seen before. And at that point a dagger seemed to twist deep inside him and he guessed that it was over before she even opened her mouth. <br />And as if on cue she delivered the words, -- It's over, Danny, with a stark, uncompromising air of finality.<br />Skinner was crushed by her words. He wished he wasn't but he was. He felt something real, something essential die inside him; felt it actually leave his body. It was a rich, deep and vital energy, a cardinal component of the self. Stricken, he wondered if he would ever get it back, or if that's what life was to be: steady erosion followed by an occasional big subsidence. He was surely too young to feel like this. His anguished gasp was deep, disturbing and primal, shocking both him and Kay." pg. 90<br /><br />"The early-morning hours slowly faded away, just as the night had slipped by in a sleepless agony. Kibby's swollen eyes ached and itched full of sleeplessness's phantom dirt. He squirmed like a beached porpoise on his sweat-soaked bed." pg. 149<br /><br />"Poor Big Rab, suffering from cirrhosis of the liver, now never able to drink again. What a nightmare. That's the problem with intoxication, it's an immediate state, belonging in the present. You can't live your life on the memory of previous consumption." pg. 220<br /><br />"Skinner realised that he'd seldom thought about a woman in purely sexual terms. Even if somebody was an object of his desire, he invariably found himself thinking about her level of intelligence, music, clothing, film and book preferences, the sort of friends she had, her social and political views, what her parents did for a living. Yes, he had got involved in one-night stands, but casual relationships were always unsatisfying to him. He looked searchingly at Kibby. -- I'm just interested in women, Brian." pg. 379 <br /><br />Book: from Derek T's collection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4773119499982378485" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


